chapter-1
=========

- What to expect from a manager
    - One-on-one meetings
        - To create human connection between you and your manager
            - Being an introvert is not an excuse
            - Trust requires willingness to be vulnerable with each other
        - To speak privately about whatever needs discussing
            - Irregular is ok, but don't eliminate them completely
            - Good one-on-ones are usually not status meetings
            - Share the responsibility of having good meetings with your manager
    - Feedback and workplace guidance
        - Not just performance reviews
        - Keep track of both good and bad feedback; use it for self-assessments
        - Ideally, feedback is public if it's praise and private if it's criticism
        - Asking advice from a manager shows respect and trust
        - Prerequisite to getting raises and promotions
        - Types of feedback and guidance include
            - Reviewing content prior to a presentation
            - Provide areas of improvement to a design document
            - Help navigating difficult situations, like working with difficult people
            - Identifying and assigning stretch projects that help with learning
            - Help understanding the value of your work, even when it's not glamorous
    - Training and career growth
        - Manager holds some responsibility in helping you find training and other resources
        - You are most responsible in figuring out what types of training you want
        - In order to get promoted
            - For less senior roles, ask your manager for specific areas of focus
            - For more senior roles, you may need to propose achievements that qualify you
- How to be managed
    - Spend time thinking about what you want
        - Use your manager to help discover what is possible
        - You need to figure out what you want to do and what will make you happy
    - You are responsible for yourself
        - Seek out feedback, including constructive feedback
        - Take constructive feedback gracefully, even when you don't agree
        - If you need or want something, speak up
        - Work-life balance starts and ends with you, not your manager
    - Give your manager a break
        - Understand that your manager cannot always make you happy
        - If starting to actively resent your manager, you probably need to find a new team
        - For more senior roles, you are expected to bring solutions, not problems
    - Choose your managers wisely
        - Your manager can make a huge difference in your career
        - Strong managers know how to play the game at their company
